Memories of the Past

By the time Arazon understood what the word monster truly meant, most of them were already leaving.

He did not realise it at first. No one ever really did. There had been no announcement to mark it, no great battle or final stand that would later be turned into legend. The world simply grew less patient over time, and in doing so, it grew older. The departure of such beings was quiet, quieter than war and even quieter than peace. It happened in the same way erosion happens, slowly and without anyone truly noticing.

Roads widened where forests once pressed close together, and fields spread into places that had held other names long before maps learned to claim them centuries later. What could not move aside was labelled an obstacle. What resisted was called dangerous. What endured was eventually named monstrous.

Arazon had grown up singing the songs that explained this change.

In those songs, monsters always came from the darkness and returned to it. They were defined by teeth, claws, and curses, given shape so that heroes could justify destroying them and earning their victories. The stories were neat, perhaps too neat, though Arazon did not think about this much at the time. They ended cleanly, usually with steel. Audiences liked them that way. They cheered, and Arazon gave them exactly what they wanted.

He learned early that people did not want complexity from a bard. They wanted reassurance. They wanted to believe that what frightened them was unnatural and temporary, something that could be driven away and forgotten by morning.

So he sang, and he was paid, and the road carried him onward.

What unsettled him were the places where the songs stopped matching what he saw.

Between towns, Arazon noticed hearthstones laid carefully in circles but long cold, as if fires had been extinguished deliberately rather than abandoned in haste. Wells had been filled in with stone and earth, sealed with too much care. Old paths worn into the ground curved away from the road and ended abruptly, leading nowhere anyone remembered going.

Sometimes he found markings half-buried beneath roots or moss — spirals, lines, and patterns worn soft by time. They were too old to frighten anyone anymore, because fear required memory, and memory of these places had faded.

When Arazon asked about them, villagers only shrugged.

“There were things here once,” they said. “Best not to ask what or who. They’re all long gone now, as they should be.”

The Hollow at Marrowfen

The first monster who listened to Arazon did so without stepping fully into the light.

He had made camp in a hollow a short walk from the village of Marrowfen. The trees there grew old and twisted, their roots knotted together like clasped hands. The villagers had warned him not to stay there. They spoke of something in the woods, though no one described it the same way twice.

Arazon stayed anyway, as he always did, and sang.

The song was an old road-ballad, steady and low, meant for long journeys made alone. It spoke of tides that carried sailors farther than they intended, and of shores that only looked familiar from a distance. It was not heroic, and it always ended without triumph.

Halfway through the second verse, Arazon felt something change.

Not movement, but attention.

He looked up slowly and saw a shape crouched just beyond the firelight. The creature was bent low, its limbs long and uneven, its skin ridged like bark after rain. It did not bare its teeth or move closer. It simply listened, its head tilted slightly, as though afraid that even breathing too loudly might disturb the sound.

Every instinct in Arazon told him to stop. Habit carried him forward instead.

When the final note faded, the forest did not immediately return to its usual sounds. Even the insects seemed to pause.

“You sing like someone who remembers,” the creature said.

Its voice was thick and muddy, like the sound of soil after rain. To Arazon, it felt as though the earth itself were speaking for the first time in a long while. The voice was slow and deliberate, but not cruel.

Arazon swallowed. His fingers hovered above the strings. “What should I remember?”

The creature shifted slightly, firelight catching in its eyes.

“The world as it was,” it said. “Before we were made into something else. The tales of the Old.”

The words settled heavily between them.

The creature remained where it was, and Arazon did not invite it closer. Some boundaries, he sensed, were kept not out of fear, but respect.

Eventually, the creature spoke again, and Arazon began to learn the shape of a history that had never been taught to him.

“Before we were called monsters,” it said, “we were simply neighbours. We had names for ourselves.”

Long before the word monster existed, there had been villages woven into the land rather than forced upon it. Homes shaped from bark, stone, and river clay rested where the ground allowed. Paths curved to spare old trees, and time was measured by moonrise and migration rather than harvests.

“We were called the Children of the Earth,” the creature said. “That was our name.”

Arazon listened without moving.

“The Old told us of humanity’s coming,” it continued. “They were meant to be fragile at first. They would need room and patience. We were given the land to tend so they could grow within it — not beneath us, not above us, but alongside us.”

It paused before adding, “And for a time, they did.”

Humans arrived slowly at first. Trade followed. Stories were exchanged. Songs crossed boundaries.

Then paths became roads.

Fields spread outward. Forests retreated. Springs were claimed and redirected. Hills were quarried down until they were useful.

The fire cracked softly.

“We sang together,” the creature said. “Not like you do. There was no audience. No stage. Just voices answering one another, and the land listening.”

Its gaze drifted into the darkness beyond the fire.

“When humans forgot the story,” it said, “they renamed us — stubborn when we would not move, dangerous when we defended what remained.”

Arazon stared into the fire, thinking of the songs he had once sung without asking how those stories began.

“They say you attacked first,” he said quietly.

“We held our ground the way a dam holds back a flood,” the creature replied. “We wanted no victory, only coexistence.”

Arazon had no answer.

Listening

The creature left before dawn. Arazon did not follow.

Three nights later, another came — smaller, pale, its joints bending at odd angles. It carried a cracked flute.

“I used to play,” it said. “Before they burned the village.”

Arazon listened.

After that, others came. Never in crowds. Always cautiously.

They did not ask Arazon to save them. They asked him to remember.

“Sing what stood here before the roads.”
“Sing the days before we learned to hide.”
“Sing that we were once more than what remains.”

Arazon stopped singing the old ballads. He began shaping quieter melodies, songs that did not explain or justify, but simply remembered.

As time passed, the hollow grew quieter.

Some nights, no one came at all.

Arazon still played.

He remembered stories of small villages, of homes that were enough, of songs sung only once a year. He remembered being told that songs were never written down because they were meant to move.

On one of his last nights in Marrowfen, no footsteps came.

He sang anyway.

The song faded into the forest and found nothing to answer it.

Only silence remained.

And Arazon understood, slowly and painfully, that he had not been teaching the Children of the Earth how to sing.

He had been learning how to listen when no one was left to speak.`,
    },
];

