Throughout this course, my understanding of storytelling, theme, and voice developed significantly through the process of drafting, revising, and refining my creative and especially analytical work. Writing the short story Remembrance alongside the accompanying story analysis and other tasks allowed me to explore how narrative perspective, restraint, and symbolism can be used to communicate complex ideas such as displacement, memory, and cultural erasure. Most importantly, the short story assignment helped me understand how inspiration from existing literary traditions particularly J. R. R. Tolkien’s melancholic portrayal of fading magic which I utilized can be adapted into an original voice rather than copied directly.

The earliest drafts of my short story focused heavily on plot and worldbuilding. I was initially concerned with establishing the fantasy setting clearly and explaining the history of the so-called “monsters.” However, as I revised the piece, I realised that over-explanation weakened the emotional impact. This led me to shift toward a quieter, more restrained style where absence, silence, and implication carried more weight than direct exposition. This approach was heavily inspired by Tolkien’s treatment of the departure of magical beings in The Lord of the Rings, where elves, ents, and other ancient creatures do not disappear through violence or conquest, but through time, change, and forgetting. That sense of inevitability where the world simply moves on became central to Remembrance.

In Tolkien’s work, the fading of magic is not framed as a tragedy or with a clear antagonist, but as a sorrowful consequence of progress and human expansion. I consciously reflected this in my portrayal of the Children of the Earth. They are not defeated or destroyed, instead they leave quietly as roads widen, forests retreat, and humans redefine the world through naming and ownership. This allowed me to explore melancholy without relying on dramatic conflict. The absence of a final battle or climactic resolution was a deliberate choice meant to mirror Tolkien’s elegiac tone and to emphasise that loss is often gradual and unnoticed.

The revision process was particularly important in achieving this effect. Feedback and self-reflection led me to remove lines that explicitly stated emotional change, such as “the listening songs changed him,” and replace them with behavioural descriptions that showed Arazon’s transformation instead. By focusing on how his hands slowed, how he left space for silence, and how he continued to sing even when no one was listening, I learned to trust the reader to interpret meaning rather than spelling it out. This was a major development in my writing, as earlier drafts relied too heavily on explanation rather than implication.

My analytical work on The Manager of ‘The Kremlin’ by Evelyn Waugh also influenced my creative decisions. Waugh’s detached narrative style and focus on displacement helped me understand how emotional restraint can make a story more powerful. Just as Boris’s suffering is presented through precise details rather than overt emotional commentary, I attempted to portray loss in Remembrance through material absence such as empty hollows, abandoned paths, and unanswered songs. This cross-application of analytical insight into creative writing strengthened both pieces and demonstrated the value of close reading as a tool for original creation.

